}
@article{Gould1979a,
annote = {Stephen Jay Gould and Richard C. Lewontin criticized the adaptationist program, "based on faith in the power of natural selection as an optimizing agent", that had dominated evolutionary thought during the last four decades. They argued that organisms must be analyzed as integrated wholes constrained by phyletic heritage, pathways of development and general architecture that become themselves more interesting and more important in delimiting pathways of change than the selective force that may mediate change when it occurs.

        
The adaptationist program proceeds first by breaking an organism into unitary traits and proposing an adaptive story for each considered separately. When interactions between parts are recognized and hence, an organism cannot optimize each part without imposing expenses of others, the notion of trade-off is introduced. Then, the adaptationist program breaks an organism into parts and tells adaptive stories as if trade-offs among competing well designed parts were the only constraint upon perfection for each trait.

        
They characterized the adaptationist program through four common styles of argument: i) "If one adaptive argument fails, try another. The failure of one adaptive explanation should always simply inspire a search for another of the same general form, rather than a consideration of alternatives to the proposition that each part is 'for' some specific purpose"; ii) "If one adaptive argument fails, assume that another must exist"; iii) "In the absence of a good adaptive argument in the first place, attribute failure to imperfect understanding of where an organism lives and what it does"; iv) "Emphasize immediate utility and exclude other attributes of form". They pointed out that "One must not confuse the fact that a structure is used in some way with the primary evolutionary reason for its existence and conformation".

        
The pluralistic spirit of Charles Darwin regarding the role of natural selection is emphasized when the authors cite his words in the last edition of the Origin: "I am convinced that natural selection has been the main, but not the exclusive means of modification".

        
They presented some alternatives to adaptation for explaining the form, function, and behavior: i) "No adaptation and no selection at all" (the role of genetic drift: how much genetic variation between populations of between species is, in fact, the result of natural selection as opposed to purely random factors); ii) "No adaptation and no selection on the part at issue: form of the part is a correlated consequence of selection directed elsewhere"; iii) "The decoupling of selection and adaptation" (selection without adaptation, and adaptation without selection); iv) "Adaptation and selection but no selective basis for differences among adaptations" (different adaptations as solutions to the same problem); v) "Adaptation and selection, but the adaptation is a secondary utilization of parts present for reasons of architecture, development or history". 

        
They concluded their paper saying: "Under the adaptationist programme, the great historic themes of developmental morphology and Bauplan were largely abandoned; for if selection can break any correlation and optimize parts separately, then an organism's integration counts for little. Too often, the adaptationist programme gave us an evolutionary biology of parts and genes, but not of organisms. It assumed that all transitions could occur step by step and underrated the importance of integrated developmental blocks and pervasive constraints of history and architecture. A pluralistic view could put organisms, with their recalcitrant, yet intelligible, complexity, back into the evolutionary theory".},
author = {Gould, S.J. and Lewontin, R.C.},
