@article{Maynard-Smith1966,
annote = {As opposed to allopatric speciation (the evolution of geographically isolated populations into distinct species), the concept of sympatric speciation introduced by John Maynard-Smith does not require geographic isolation to occur. In this case, the speciation from a single ancestral species inhabiting the same geographic region occurs without any constraint to interbreeding (see also Maynard-Smith, Disruptive selection, polymorphism and sympatric speciation, 1962).

        
The idea can be explained by the exploitation of different niches. For example, if individuals laid their eggs and tend to look for mates on the type of niche they grew up in, females and males will end up mating with other individuals from the same niche. This means that gene flow between two subsets of the population that mate on two different niches is reduced. This niche preference could maintain a stable polymorphism and may be the first step toward sympatric speciation. 

        
Maynard-Smith summarized, at the end of the paper, the conditions for a stable polymorphism to exist: "It is shown that in a heterogeneous environment divided into two "niches", a stable polymorphism can exist between two alleles each conferring a selective advantage in one of the niches, even if adults form a single random mating population, provided: (1) the population size is separately regulated in the two niches, and (2) the selective advantages are large."

        
There was a strong controversy about the concept of sympatric speciation that still persists nowadays. Ernest Mayr completely rejected it. Maynard-Smith made this explicit at the beginning of the paper, citing one of Mayr's criticisms: "On would think that it should no longer be necessary to devote much time to this topic, but past experience permits one to predict that the issue will be raised again at regular intervals" (Mayr, Animal species and evolution, 1963).

      },
